05293nam a22008175i 9780812208467DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577386  a97808122084677 a10.9783/97808122084672doi  a(DE-B1597)449757  a(OCoLC)858843169  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0160002bisacsh04a323.1196/07309052231 aGlaser, James M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChanging Minds, If Not Hearts :bPolitical Remedies for Racial Conflict /cJames M. Glaser, Timothy J. Ryan. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Governance: Politics, Policy, and Public Law00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tChapter 1. burdens of our past -- tChapter 2. ballot architecture and the building of schools -- tChapter 3. following neighbors, if not leaders -- tChapter 4. remorse, retribution, and restoration -- tChapter 5. a panoply of preferences -- tChapter 6. a spotlight on race neutrality -- tChapter 7. changing minds, if not hearts -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmericans preach egalitarianism, but democracy makes it hard for minorities to win. Changing Minds, If Not Hearts explores political strategies that counteract the impulse of racial majorities to think about racial issues as a zero-sum game, in which a win for one group means a loss for another. James M. Glaser and Timothy J. Ryan argue that, although political processes often inflame racial tensions, the tools of politics also can alleviate conflict.Through randomized experiments conducted in South Carolina, California, Michigan, Mississippi, Oklahoma, and New Jersey, Glaser and Ryan uncover the racial underpinnings of disputes over affirmative action, public school funding initiatives, Confederate flag displays on government buildings, reparations, and racial profiling. The authors examine whether communities rife with conflict endorse different outcomes when issues are cast in different terms—for example, by calling attention to double standards, evoking alternate conceptions of fairness and justice, or restructuring electoral choices to offer voters greater control. Their studies identify a host of tools that can help overcome opposition to minority interests that are due to racial hostility. Even in communities averse to accommodation, even where antipathy and prejudice linger, minorities can win.With clearly presented data and compelling prose, Changing Minds, If Not Hearts provides a vivid and practical illustration of how academic theory can help resolve conflicts on the ground.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitical activityy21st century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmenty21st century. 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 0aRacexPolitical aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aRyan, Timothy J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220846740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978081